	doi = {10.1086/424032},
	abstract = {The evolution in the comoving space density of the global average galaxy star formation rate (SFR) out to a redshift around unity is well established. Beyond z{\textasciitilde}1 there is growing evidence that this evolution is flat or even increasing, contrary to early indications of a turnover. Some recent analyses of z{\textasciitilde}6 photometric dropouts are suggestive of a decline from z=3 to z{\textasciitilde}6, but there is still very little constraint on the extent of dust obscuration at such high redshifts. In less than a decade, numerous measurements of galaxy SFR density spanning z=0 to as high as z{\textasciitilde}6 have rapidly broadened our understanding of galaxy evolution, and a summary of existing SFR density measurements is presented here. This global star formation history compilation is found to be consistent to within factors of about 3 over essentially the entire range 0Q] and density evolution [φ{\textasciitilde}(1+z)P] is found. Combining the constraints from the global SFR density evolution with those from the 1.4 GHz radio source counts at submillijansky levels allows this degeneracy to be broken and a best-fitting evolutionary form to be established. The preferred evolution in a H0=70,ΩM=0.3,ΩΛ=0.7 cosmology from these combined constraints is Q=2.70+/-0.60, P=0.15+/-0.60.},
